WEBVTT

00:02.883 --> 00:09.512
This is Deborah Beale, and I am interviewing Dr. 
David Norton on the history of the Texas

00:02.883 --> 00:09.512
Engineering Experiment Station. The date is June 
12, 1984. Are you ready to go ahead and start? And

00:16.702 --> 00:18.645
I'd like to start with just a little background. 
Let's start with your education and how you came to

00:18.745 --> 00:21.549
come here. OK. Let's see. You want to start at the 
college level of education? I came to A&M in 1958.

00:33.511 --> 00:48.365
as a student in mechanical engineering and did an 
ME, a bachelor of science, and then a master's of

00:33.511 --> 00:48.365
science. I graduated in 63

00:48.385 --> 01:00.396
and then went to Purdue and did a PhD in mechanical 
engineering and specialized in propulsion.

01:01.557 --> 01:07.204
Then, having been commissioned here, I was then 
ready for active duty. So I did active duty in the

01:08.525 --> 01:23.923
Ordnance Corps and was eventually assigned to the 
Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena,

01:08.525 --> 01:23.923
California on my tour of active duty after an 
officer's basic in the East Coast. Then I was out

01:23.944 --> 01:26.907
there two years. And then in January of 1970, I took 
an appointment here as an assistant professor in

01:28.135 --> 01:37.448
the aerospace engineering department. So I 
stayed in that capacity until January of 1982,

01:37.468 --> 01:48.344
basically. And which time I came over here and 
began as an assistant director for what was then

01:48.364 --> 01:56.235
called program. and am now the assistant director 
of research. When did you first become aware of

02:02.443 --> 02:06.469
Tunis? Probably my second day here. As a student or 
as a... No, not really as a student at all.

02:18.768 --> 02:26.560
Even my graduate research days

02:18.768 --> 02:26.560
in the early 60s, late 50s, TEAS, as you'll be 
finding out, was not as pervasive an influence as

02:27.181 --> 02:35.734
it is today in engineering research. For example, 
the mechanical engineering department really

02:37.176 --> 02:52.378
didn't interface a great deal with engineering 
department section, although a few faculty had

02:37.176 --> 02:52.378
done work through them and with them during the war 
and after. They operated the mechanical

02:53.624 --> 03:10.060
engineering department separately and worked 
out assistantships and fellowships separately

02:53.624 --> 03:10.060
and didn't really have much of a research program. 
As a matter of fact, the reason many of the colleges

03:10.080 --> 03:18.889
didn't have a real research program were only 
doing a very nominal amount of graduate work. and

03:19.409 --> 03:24.275
the need for funded research was not as large as it 
is today. So, it just really wasn't that pervasive

03:24.295 --> 03:28.600
of a factor. What was your first project through 
TEAS? Well, the excitement that brought me here,

03:32.485 --> 03:40.035
as opposed to the other places I was looking at, was 
the Space Shuttle. Professor Al Kronk, who was the

03:40.055 --> 03:42.818
department head at that time, in the interview 
process indicated to me that he had been asked by

03:43.051 --> 03:57.708
Johnson Spacecraft Center to develop capability 
in dealing with shuttle problems. And

03:57.728 --> 04:03.835
specifically, they had problems with 
propulsion, which was my specialty. So the offer

04:03.895 --> 04:08.721
to get involved and begin to do research on space 
shuttles was my inducement to come here because

04:09.460 --> 04:27.536
that was a major new exciting program that had all 
the disciplines that I was interested in going

04:09.460 --> 04:27.536
with it and it was yet had an applied side that was 
appealing to me that I'd be able to see this thing

04:09.460 --> 04:27.536
designed, developed, flown over the years. So 
that's the reason I came and that's the first

04:27.556 --> 04:31.860
research project. It was, I was under contract in 
NASA basically continuously for the next 12 years

04:31.880 --> 04:38.185
on this mission. I don't know if this is directly 
related to the propulsion, but the wind tunnel was

04:39.397 --> 04:45.907
used for that. Do you know what it was used for 
immediately before that? Before that major

04:48.852 --> 04:56.964
relationship was established between JSC and our 
air department, I think it was used to store hay.

04:57.646 --> 05:04.917
There was a period of time where it was basically 
unused or used sporadically at best in the 60s. As

05:04.937 --> 05:06.940
far as I could tell, It was basically unused for a 
period of time until the late 60s. In 69, it took

05:11.860 --> 05:30.784
some aid of NASA, old equipment, old recorder, old 
stuff, and some people that were sent up here to

05:11.860 --> 05:30.784
help us get modernized from JSC, a guy named Ray 
Moore.

05:30.804 --> 05:35.290
We had a lot of help from them in trying to get us 
developed as a facility where they could come do

05:36.620 --> 05:49.472
some testing and some evaluation that they would 
otherwise have to go to one of the major NASA

05:36.620 --> 05:49.472
centers, Langley or Ames, or hire down at one of the 
contractors, where they wouldn't really be a

05:36.620 --> 05:49.472
party to the work. So they could actually come in 
the lab and turn their roller shirt sleeves up, get

05:49.993 --> 05:58.621
in there and feel what was going on in a friendly, 
cooperative environment. And that's what they

05:58.641 --> 06:05.327
were looking for to establish here, and they did.

06:05.864 --> 06:08.527
change from director of programs to director of 
research. Was that a real change in the jobs? No, it

06:12.171 --> 06:13.332
was not. It was a change or a different 
recognition, I think, in that the research, the

06:13.493 --> 06:20.441
purpose of engineering firm station is research. 
It's not business. It's not research. And this, in

06:24.185 --> 06:33.856
essence, made it clear that this was, I was 
interested in a research position that led to, you

06:24.185 --> 06:33.856
know, the main heartbeat. I wasn't a peripheral I 
wasn't in anything else but Missouri. What is your

06:39.233 --> 06:40.575
job now? What do you do? My job and most of the jobs I 
already have is what I want it to be, basically.

06:52.709 --> 07:04.423
What I want it to be is developing the research 
potential of TEAS and Texas A&M for the benefit of

06:52.709 --> 07:04.423
the state. I'm very clear about that role. In my 
opinion, the role is to make the infrastructure,

07:11.476 --> 07:24.831
the technical infrastructure of Texas be as 
strong as possible. And at the same time, to

07:24.851 --> 07:29.736
develop that in the sense of research capability 
and technical manpower. The technical manpower

07:33.230 --> 07:55.620
we developed basically by providing assistance 
to graduate students through work, not through

07:33.230 --> 07:55.620
gifts, through work and assistantship and buying 
millions of dollars of equipment that is used for

07:33.230 --> 07:55.620
research but also is used to teach at the graduate 
and senior level of the undergraduate program. So

07:55.640 --> 08:00.246
in that way we developed the capabilities and the 
technical manpower pool. And we also take all this

08:00.698 --> 08:14.610
intellect that's here and make it, otherwise it's 
not available, make it available to the benefit of

08:00.698 --> 08:14.610
the state.

08:15.972 --> 08:22.637
To do that, you have to have a large enough pool that 
you have a group that can do almost anything. And

08:23.578 --> 08:30.064
when the state has a need, you are simply the 
conduit into that pool to apply it. And then when

08:31.411 --> 08:36.137
that need goes away, you tap into another part of 
the pool for another problem. You have to have this

08:36.157 --> 08:52.376
pool, and that takes a lot of work and support to 
keep that pool of 400 or 500 engineers going here,

08:36.157 --> 08:52.376
keep them bubbling up and exciting the students 
and developing their capabilities so that

08:36.157 --> 08:52.376
they're available. If you only had 100, you 
wouldn't be able to serve that role. You wouldn't

08:56.180 --> 09:00.085
be able to say, whatever the problem is, we have the 
talent. It takes this level of a group to keep the

09:00.925 --> 09:06.331
process going. How did you first get involved in 
administration of TEAS? Skip Porter called me. He

09:12.738 --> 09:14.360
said, I want you to be assistant director. I told 
him no twice. Finally, I told him yes. We started

09:19.606 --> 09:25.652
out on a half-time basis, a three-quarter time 
basis, and finally a full-time basis. Because I

09:25.672 --> 09:28.215
had other things that I was doing in Arrow. I was now 
a full professor over there, traveling

09:28.887 --> 09:32.835
internationally in my own research. I developed 
an environmental aerodynamics laboratory, and

09:34.358 --> 09:46.521
we were starting to do three, four hundred 
thousand dollars worth of research, and junior

09:34.358 --> 09:46.521
faculty and graduate students. Things were 
really bubbling over there. It was for some

09:49.981 --> 10:02.117
reluctance that I consider that, because I'm by no 
stretch of imagination, at least initially

09:49.981 --> 10:02.117
configured for administrative work. My 
strengths have always been the technical,

10:03.279 --> 10:15.195
personal sort of commitment, as opposed to 
getting other people to do things, but you can

10:03.279 --> 10:15.195
learn some of the skills. When did you get the 
environmental aerodynamics portion? No, it

10:19.447 --> 10:20.147
wasn't before. Environmental aerodynamics 
later. OK. OK, at this point, someplace around in

10:21.990 --> 10:43.596
the mid, another element of the story, my personal 
story, is about the mid-'70s, the enrollment of

10:21.990 --> 10:43.596
aerospace engineering, as an example, went from 
100, say, like 200 freshmen in the fall of 72 to like

10:21.990 --> 10:43.596
60 freshmen in the fall of 73. So there was a 
precipitous step function in enrollment. And in

10:51.133 --> 11:06.947
order to maintain the faculty, there were about 
nine or 10 at that time, active full-time faculty,

10:51.133 --> 11:06.947
it was clear that we were going to have to diversify 
and go heavily into research instead of being

10:51.133 --> 11:06.947
quarter-time research, be pre-quarter-time 
research. And those of us that looked around and

11:06.967 --> 11:10.350
said, well, where is the money? Where are we going 
to do that? We all did our own thing individually

11:14.677 --> 11:17.322
sought out other areas, or broaden their own 
areas. And one of the things I looked at was

11:18.324 --> 11:23.173
something called environmental aerodynamics, 
which is not propulsion. It is the flow of wind and

11:23.193 --> 11:31.369
its effect on man, buildings, and the sea, and 
offshore platforms, things like that. And

11:32.652 --> 11:37.461
at that time, that was something that was being 
developed nationwide. I went to Colorado State

11:40.634 --> 11:48.324
for eight weeks to where the United States' most 
prestigious guy is named Cermak. I spent eight

11:49.265 --> 11:52.890
weeks with him learning this branch of 
engineering. I brought that back here and over the

11:53.591 --> 11:59.099
next several years developed that as an area of 
study. I developed two courses, graduate courses

12:00.000 --> 12:04.326
and an area of research. So I did a great deal of 
that, in addition to whatever little bits of NASA

12:04.728 --> 12:13.364
work that was still to be done. Was this the group 
that was involved in the oil, or were you involved

12:13.765 --> 12:18.614
in the oil spill research? No. Well, yes, I have 
been involved in oil spill research, but not from

12:19.315 --> 12:28.592
the point of view of Roy Hand, who goes out when 
there's an oil spill and goes out and tries to

12:29.602 --> 12:32.825
analyze the situation and stuff like that. My 
involvement has been in terms of the fluid

12:32.845 --> 12:38.451
mechanics of how you skim it off the water. Well, 
that's the research that was done in the mid-'70s,

12:38.471 --> 12:42.555
right? Mm-hmm, right. And it developed a training 
program for them? Mm-hmm, eventually, yes,

12:46.059 --> 12:47.721
right. Did that start with the beginning of that 
lab? No, that lab was created, I think, about 1980.

12:55.329 --> 12:59.473
No, we were just loosely associated with people 
around the campus that were doing work in oil

12:59.875 --> 13:10.915
spill, and there was people in civil engineering, 
myself and Arrow and other people, and that was one

12:59.875 --> 13:10.915
of those opportunities that came along that I got 
involved with about two years. Whose brainchild

13:11.997 --> 13:13.119
was that? I don't know, it may go back to, I know 
Charlie Rodenberger was involved with a contract

13:14.140 --> 13:22.896
with the Department of Transportation. And it 
involved the Coast Guard, in which they were

13:23.922 --> 13:31.593
trying to find mechanisms to contain oil spill to 
sea, especially when there were the current.

13:32.574 --> 13:38.022
Because the booms that they had, the oil would just 
go unneeded, pile up against one side and get so

13:32.574 --> 13:38.022
deep and then go unneeded. So they were looking for 
ways to combat that tendency. And that's the kind

13:41.828 --> 13:44.952
of research that at least I was involved in. In the 
early and mid-'70s with the energy crisis, did

13:46.028 --> 13:53.620
that change the direction of your research? Not so 
much, except that one of the areas of research that

13:54.482 --> 14:01.814
I began to look at was generation of wind power by 
wind. So I added that into the things that we were

14:02.495 --> 14:06.822
doing in my lectures and courses. So I brought in 
that sense, but I didn't, I wasn't never just

14:07.392 --> 14:12.899
fundamentally in energy research. Did money for 
that type of thing become more readily available

14:12.919 --> 14:17.225
at that point? Uh, sure. And many, many people 
around the campus, like in chemical engineering

14:18.306 --> 14:30.302
and other places, lacked on to that, and that 
concept didn't get involved in a great deal of

14:18.306 --> 14:30.302
research. Everything from oil shales and all 
kinds of things. But I never personally got

14:34.307 --> 14:37.011
involved, not too much. But that was the time in 
which people began to do that, to get some of that

14:37.447 --> 14:42.652
Department of Energy money. Did you find that with

14:44.014 --> 14:56.706
the late 70s, when the popularity of the space 
program went downhill, was it harder to get money

14:44.014 --> 14:56.706
for your research? Sure. That's the reason why I 
was still doing work for them. It was not something

15:04.092 --> 15:11.479
that would be a full-time research activity, and 
so I needed to develop a parallel. Is that the same

15:11.499 --> 15:13.321
reason they're dropping students? Yeah, right. 
So there wasn't that much teaching. So... Not only

15:16.203 --> 15:20.587
did you have trouble getting money, but you didn't 
have the students as well? That's right. Okay. So

15:22.049 --> 15:31.738
you really had... You know, there was... Nobody 
would fire you, but on the other hand, you had a

15:22.049 --> 15:31.738
sense to keep the team together. And now we have... 
Well, we now have the largest aerospace

15:34.619 --> 15:38.424
engineering department in the country. We have 
something like 700 students, which is by far and

15:38.444 --> 15:41.749
away. We were down to like 100 students total. But 
we had the same teams there. And they're there

15:46.897 --> 15:51.603
because when the time came, we knew what to do to 
keep ourselves there. And so the role of playing

15:52.925 --> 16:01.537
back and forth between research and teaching and 
engineering, which is cyclical, is absolutely

15:52.925 --> 16:01.537
critical. If you don't have that flexibility, 
you're not going to make too many perturbations in

16:03.762 --> 16:07.205
this field. The aerospace is coming back. Oh, 
yeah. It's here. When did this new wave start?

16:15.973 --> 16:20.717
Well, it really started like a year or two after the 
big low. We've been plotting a curve. It's been

16:22.839 --> 16:24.721
going like that ever since. It's just been 10% per 
year or 20% per year, and it's just been going,

16:24.801 --> 16:29.104
going, going. What do you think precipitated 
that? Well, I think the next thing that

16:33.412 --> 16:36.977
Historically, it was the space shuttle. In 1969, 
we had landing on the moon, and we had the rest of the

16:37.557 --> 16:42.664
Apollo. And the Apollo came, and that was, oh, 
we're on the moon again. It just lost interest.

16:49.613 --> 16:50.774
Then we had a gap there. And meanwhile, in 1969, we 
started working on the shuttle. And it did its

16:54.599 --> 16:59.385
first flights in the mid-1974 or 75, I guess. so 
that was the next big big thing so about 75 the

16:59.855 --> 17:22.285
shuttle then they dropped tested it off the 747 and 
they did this they did that so that's uh begin to

16:59.855 --> 17:22.285
reawaken the american public a little bit but that 
and i think other things uh i think

17:23.750 --> 17:30.777
reconsideration of what we would do in defense, 
which is, of course, a big implore of aerospace

17:23.750 --> 17:30.777
people.

17:32.338 --> 17:41.006
Pretty good time as far as the airlines were 
concerned, and major programs to develop the 757

17:32.338 --> 17:41.006
and the 767. There was a number of little things 
that kept things parking alone. Who do you deal

17:47.432 --> 17:52.677
with as an administrator inside the system, 
inside the teams? That's the answer I'm getting

17:53.095 --> 17:57.082
from everybody. No, primarily it would be TASE, 
N-T-A-M-U, and in some cases other universities

17:57.102 --> 18:16.116
in the system, Prairie View, and also other 
research entities that are in this stage around

17:57.102 --> 18:16.116
the nation. How about outside the system? Who do 
you usually meet with? Well, we meet with the

18:23.472 --> 18:25.294
University of Texas at Arlington. I mean, this 
year I probably had four or five meetings with the

18:25.314 --> 18:33.826
University of Texas at Austin in terms of the water 
research and other things that we're trying to

18:25.314 --> 18:33.826
coordinate, you know, the feeling of cooperation 
with UT. Is that a new feeling? What? Is that a

18:35.669 --> 18:37.451
feeling of cooperation new? Yeah, it was, you 
know, right, right, fairly new. The last few

18:41.617 --> 18:42.799
years? The last two years. I think it's an impetus 
of the posture that the chancellors

18:45.188 --> 18:53.038
take. Do you deal with them in the state or national 
legislature? Yeah, we have the speaker of the

19:00.567 --> 19:10.098
house, Texas House here, and a couple of 
representatives. So yeah, we deal with this.

19:11.660 --> 19:13.002
We're a state agency. A lot of things happen over 
here that don't necessarily go through the

19:13.538 --> 19:21.929
university, so people come here and see the 
research. I know Jane Armstrong is the liaison.

19:25.033 --> 19:27.497
Yeah, she is our primary liaison. So are you the 
liaison with most of the other academic

19:27.557 --> 19:30.601
institutions? Yes. That would be right. When it 
comes to research and engineering research,

19:33.204 --> 19:42.837
probably that would be more what I would be doing 
when it comes to legislature or other Chamber of

19:43.171 --> 19:50.421
Commerce, other kinds of liaison that we want to 
build, Jane just generally is there. But we don't

19:50.441 --> 19:56.250
have any written instructions on that. How have 
changes in administration changed the way TEAS

19:56.891 --> 20:09.368
functions from your viewpoint?

20:09.388 --> 20:11.271
Well, first place, I came here when Fred Benson was 
in charge of most everything. So there was no

20:17.375 --> 20:23.343
changes for a decade or so. Between 1970 and 1978 or 
not, there were no changes. Then we had our big new

20:29.070 --> 20:41.106
organization and

20:29.070 --> 20:41.106
things have been sort of in a turmoil in terms of 
that ever since. That really has no effect in some

20:42.048 --> 20:47.293
senses, or it has all the effect. It just depends 
how much you want to watch it.

20:52.839 --> 20:58.104
I think we've been able to be as effective as we are 
because we've tried not to concentrate on it too

20:52.839 --> 20:58.104
much. We have a little expression we use around 
here. We like to just keep laying bricks. Let

21:05.932 --> 21:09.996
everybody else worry about it, but we just want to 
put another brick down. So that's really been what

21:10.212 --> 21:28.410
I've, while all those things have been happening, 
my feeling is that we just ought to continue to get

21:10.212 --> 21:28.410
opportunities to do research and continue to 
identify those who do the research and just keep

21:10.212 --> 21:28.410
our relationships at a high level. The funding 
agency is keeping going. Have there been any

21:31.533 --> 21:39.561
particular points in your memory, too, that have 
been some low points?

21:40.908 --> 21:46.513
when this broke down or was threatened? Well, I 
would say no.

21:51.937 --> 21:59.964
It's been very general, very high plane of 
professional activity over here all the way

21:51.937 --> 21:59.964
through. At least certainly my dealings with 
Skidport. So I haven't had the feeling, maybe a

22:05.749 --> 22:10.493
little lately,

22:15.670 --> 22:23.081
that we weren't able to take advantage of all the 
opportunities we could because things aren't

22:15.670 --> 22:23.081
settled in the administration. But it's factors 
external that's really keeping who we see dead

22:23.101 --> 22:31.694
ends because you can't get decisions or people are 
in place. You can't hire the people you want to

22:32.335 --> 22:36.001
because the apartment is not there, et cetera, et 
cetera. So those kind of things, but not as far as us

22:36.021 --> 22:43.172
within TEAS. We feel like that. There's

22:45.640 --> 22:55.412
plenty

22:45.640 --> 22:55.412
of opportunities to take advantage of it if the 
rest of the people want to. How much influence has

22:55.432 --> 23:00.758
the Research Foundation had on your work? The 
Research Foundation, I have a long history with

23:00.778 --> 23:04.282
the Research Foundation. I bet if you went over 
there you'd find that I've had more contracts with

23:04.302 --> 23:15.175
the Research Foundation than any researcher

23:04.302 --> 23:15.175
on campus. As a researcher dealing with the 
Research Foundation, although there have been

23:16.505 --> 23:34.364
minor frustrations, I've always felt that they 
were trying to help the researcher and

23:16.505 --> 23:34.364
there were such good people out there. What is not 
commonly understood by the faculty is that

23:42.053 --> 24:01.355
Research Foundation is indeed not an entity of the 
Texas A&M University System and employs no

23:42.053 --> 24:01.355
professional research faculty and is indeed a 
place to make things easier by verging on the fact

23:42.053 --> 24:01.355
that it's not part of Texas A&M. And I think if you 
would ask a typical new faculty member that he

24:01.375 --> 24:09.765
thinks he works for the Research Foundation and I 
think that they try to make them,

24:10.488 --> 24:19.037
not directly, but indirectly. And that causes 
some confusion as to who they report to, who's

24:19.057 --> 24:34.873
responsible for their political tenure, who are 
the people, indeed, that

24:19.057 --> 24:34.873
they should look to for their long-term support 
group. So in that sense, it's confusing to find

24:35.894 --> 24:39.297
out. And

24:40.137 --> 24:45.885
that's not a plus. On the other side, there are 
times when they handle kind of details that really

24:46.145 --> 24:52.114
nobody wants to get involved with. People want to 
take the time complying with OSHA and complying

24:52.194 --> 25:02.128
with all the federal regulations that apply to a 
contract and all the bookkeeping and such. They

25:02.148 --> 25:05.993
provide a valuable service.

25:08.420 --> 25:15.790
Were

25:08.420 --> 25:15.790
most of your contracts through them also 
involving teams? Sure, because any research I did

25:16.330 --> 25:19.454
involved teams. The contract would usually read, 
uh, the Research Foundation checks this contract

25:19.474 --> 25:32.812
and is named the Texas Engineering Experiment 
Station as the entity who will do the research. And

25:32.832 --> 25:37.077
the Texas Engineering Experiment Station is 
named Dr. Norton as the principal investigator.

25:37.985 --> 25:44.196
So every bit of research that I've ever done over 
the last 15 years has always been the engineering

25:37.985 --> 25:44.196
term extension. Now, only in the last few years has 
it been possible to do contracts directly with the

25:44.216 --> 25:54.095
engineering term extension without the research 
foundation involved at all. But I've always been a

25:55.978 --> 25:57.501
teaser for it. I've always gotten two or three 
paychecks, different ones. So, what is the

26:03.061 --> 26:09.351
difference between teams and researchers? Well, 
the Research Foundation is a not-for-profit,

26:09.371 --> 26:28.984
arm's length corporation that was set up to 
circumvent purchasing regulations in the state

26:09.371 --> 26:28.984
of Texas. for the purpose of doing,

